    "content": "The United Arab Emirates is expanding military facilities at Berbera Airport in the breakaway region of Somaliland, according to a report by the French newspaper Le Monde. The project, which includes the construction of new tarmacs and hangars, is based on satellite imagery, European security sources, and military analysts cited by the newspaper.\n\nConstruction activity at the site has reportedly accelerated since December 2025, when Israel was said to have recognized Somaliland’s sovereignty. While the report suggests the infrastructure could support operations involving the UAE, Israel, and the United States, Somaliland authorities have consistently denied any Israeli military base in their territory.\n\nThe Berbera corridor has long been a strategic asset, with the UAE operating a civilian-military facility under a 2017 concession agreement. This latest expansion raises questions about regional power dynamics, particularly given Somaliland’s unresolved international status and its proximity to conflict zones in Yemen and the Red Sea.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, the development underscores the shifting geopolitical landscape in the Horn of Africa. Many diaspora members have ties to both Somaliland and Somalia and closely watch such moves as indicators of future stability or conflict. The growing foreign military footprint near the Gulf of Aden could affect trade routes and security for Somali communities worldwide.\n\nThe United Arab Emirates has not publicly commented on the scope of its military construction at Berbera. Somaliland officials maintain that no foreign bases exist in the territory beyond those permitted under existing agreements.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/07/uae-constructing-strategic-military-infrastructure-in-berbera/?utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=uae-constructing-strategic-military-infrastructure-in-berbera",
