    "slug": "turkey-mediates-pre-talks-between-somali-government-and-opposition-as-puntland-jubaland-withdraw",
    "summary": "Turkish intelligence officials hosted preliminary discussions with Somalia's federal government and opposition leaders, but representatives from Puntland and Jubaland boycotted the meeting, citing concerns over Turkey's neutrality in the political crisis.",
    "content": "Turkish intelligence officials convened preliminary talks on Tuesday in Mogadishu with representatives of Somalia's federal government and opposition leaders, ahead of internationally mediated negotiations scheduled for Thursday. The meeting aimed to lay the groundwork for broader political dialogue, but delegates from the regional administrations of Puntland and Jubaland refused to attend, arguing that Turkey cannot serve as an impartial mediator in Somalia's internal affairs.\n\nDuring the session, Turkish officials expressed their desire to independently facilitate the political talks, though they acknowledged regret that Somalia's opposition and some federal member states do not share that confidence. The boycotts highlight deepening divisions between the federal government and regional states over the electoral process and power-sharing arrangements.\n\nThese pre-talks come amid ongoing tensions over Somalia's electoral framework, with opposition leaders and regional administrations demanding a return to universal suffrage, while the federal government advocates for an indirect voting model. Turkey has historically played a mediating role in Somali politics, but its perceived alignment with the current administration has drawn criticism from some factions.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, these negotiations hold significant implications, as political stability in Somalia directly affects remittances, investment, and community ties. A credible and inclusive dialogue process is essential to prevent further fragmentation that could disrupt development and security gains. The diaspora often serves as a bridge between domestic political factions and international partners, amplifying calls for transparency and inclusivity.\n\nThe scheduled Thursday negotiations will now proceed without Puntland and Jubaland, raising questions about the legitimacy and effectiveness of any outcomes. Analysts warn that continued boycotts may deepen the political impasse, potentially fueling unrest and complicating international efforts to stabilize the country.\nRead the original report from Somalia Guardian here: https://www.somaliguardian.com/news/somalia-news/turkey-somalia-opposition-talks-puntland-jubaland-boycott/",
